description:
What: generate_eui64() hashes the hardware ID to produce an EUI-64 but does not validate the entropy of the hwid. It only checks hwid_len > 0 and hwid_len <= sizeof(hwid).

Why it matters: Some MCUs return low-entropy hardware IDs:
1. Development boards may have all-zeros or sequential IDs
2. Flash-based hwids could be erased/corrupted
3. Very short hwids (e.g., 2 bytes) provide minimal collision resistance

The code relies on SHA-256 for collision resistance, but garbage-in-garbage-out applies. Multiple devices with same hwid would get same EUI-64, breaking mesh routing.

Evidence:
```c
hwid_len = hwinfo_get_device_id(hwid, sizeof(hwid));
if (hwid_len < 0) { ... }
if (hwid_len == 0) { ... }
if ((size_t)hwid_len > sizeof(hwid)) { ... }
// No entropy/quality check on hwid contents
ret = lichen_sha256(hwid, (size_t)hwid_len, hash);
```

Recommendation: Log a warning if hwid appears to be all-zeros or all-ones pattern.
